ants-terminal (0.6.34-1) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Decouples PTY read and VT parsing from the Qt GUI thread. A new
    VtStream worker QThread (src/vtstream.{h,cpp}) owns Pty and
    VtParser; parsed VtAction batches ship back to GUI over
    Qt::QueuedConnection and are applied to TerminalGrid there.
    Heavy streams (find /, cat biglog) no longer block scroll and
    repaint.
  * Back-pressure: worker buffers up to 8 batches (~128 KB of
    unprocessed PTY bytes) before disabling its read notifier so the
    kernel applies flow control to the child; GUI re-enables reads
    on drain. Replaces unbounded RAM growth with kernel-natural
    flow control.
  * Pty::setReadEnabled(bool) added for the back-pressure path.
    Pty::write and Pty::resize moved into public slots: so they can
    be invoked cross-thread via QMetaObject::invokeMethod.
  * All PTY-write call sites in TerminalWidget route through a new
    ptyWrite() helper that branches on worker-active vs. legacy
    path. Keystrokes, bracketed paste, Kitty keyboard protocol,
    response callbacks, snippets, scratchpad — correctness is
    centralised in one place.
  * Resize path uses Qt::BlockingQueuedConnection so the PTY
    winsize is updated before resizeEvent returns. Next paint
    always sees consistent ws_row/ws_col vs grid dims — no 1-frame
    flicker at the new size with old PTY dims.
  * Session logging and asciicast timestamps are now sampled on
    the worker at batch-flush time rather than on GUI at
    onPtyData time. Asciicast recordings are more accurate under
    paint load; log-file writes are per-batch (coarser than
    per-PTY-read, still monotonic).
  * Three feature-conformance tests lock the threading invariants:
    threaded_parse_equivalence (11 fixtures × 6 chunking
    strategies, pins action-stream identity),
    threaded_response_ordering (DA1/CPR/DA2/mode-996/DSR-OK across
    3 feed strategies), and threaded_resize_synchronous
    (source-level BlockingQueuedConnection contract).
  * Kill switch: set ANTS_SINGLE_THREADED=1 in the environment to
    force the legacy single-threaded path while the new code proves
    itself. The escape hatch will be removed in a follow-up release.

